    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/rh-index-comparison-operating-points",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative Hemolysis Index Comparison Across Five CPB Operating Points",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/hemolysis-experimental-measurements",
      "description": "The CFD model was exercised across the five flow-speed combinations specified in the COU (2 L/min at 2000 RPM, 3 L/min at 2500 RPM, 4 L/min at 3000 RPM, 5 L/min at 3500 RPM, and 6 L/min at 4000 RPM). For each operating point, the relative hemolysis index RH was computed by integrating the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage model along Lagrangian particle tracks seeded uniformly at the pump inlet. Experimental hemolysis measurements were obtained from an in-vitro loop using bovine blood (hematocrit 33 ± 2 %) with the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry machined to nominal tolerances. The predicted RH values ranged from 0.61 to 0.94 across the five operating points, compared with experimentally measured normalized index values of 0.58 to 0.91, yielding a maximum relative error of 5.4 % and a mean absolute error of 3.1 %. All predicted RH values remained below the acceptance threshold of 1.0. Mesh sensitivity was confirmed at the 4 L/min, 3000 RPM condition using three mesh densities (4.2 M, 9.7 M, and 18.3 M cells); the Richardson-extrapolated GCI for the scalar hemolysis index was 1.8 %, indicating negligible discretization error. Turbulence was modelled with the SST k-ω closure; wall y+ values were maintained below 1.0 on all wetted surfaces. The simulation campaign was executed on the university HPC cluster over a period of 14 days in Q3 2025, with run logs archived in the institutional repository under accession MOR-CFD-2025-047. Convergence was declared when residuals dropped below 1 × 10⁻⁶ for all transported quantities and the hemolysis scalar monitor varied by less than 0.05 % over the final 500 iterations. Post-processing scripts (Python 3.11, NumPy 1.26, SciPy 1.11) were version-controlled under tag v2.3.1 in the project GitLab repository. The detailed narrative of the simulation campaign, including boundary condition specification, material property sources, and uncertainty contributors, is documented in technical report MOR-TR-2025-003, which is available in the project dossier. This result constitutes the primary quantitative evidence supporting the credibility claim that the CFD model correctly ranks hemolysis severity across CPB operating conditions."
    },
